By using bitmask dynamic programming, the algorithm transforms the problem from a brute-force search of
× 2), which is feasible for N up to 15 to 20 (Kaçar, Kaan). Compared to more
efficient heuristics such as Christofides’ algorithm or the nearest-neighbour heuristic, dynamic programming
always guarantees the optimal solution, while heuristics only provide an approximation (GeeksForGeeks).
An iterative approach was adopted because recursion could lead to stack overflow and increase
computational complexity. The bottom-up dynamic programming approach builds up the solution from
smaller subproblems to obtaining the final answer, which optimizes performance and memory usage.
